# API Endpoints

## Add New Word

### Request

```http
POST /api/words
```

### Body

```json
{
  "word": "read"
}
```

### Response

```json
{
  "_id": "...",
  "word": "read",
  "definition": "...",
  "example": "...",
  "nextReviewDate": "..."
}
```

---

## Get All Words

### Request

```http
GET /api/words
```

Returns all saved vocabulary words.

---

## Get Review Queue

### Request

```http
GET /api/review
```

Returns all words due for review.

---

## Submit Review

### Request

```http
POST /api/review/:id
```

### Body

```json
{
  "result": "correct",
  "devMode": false
}
```

Possible values:

```json
correct
wrong
```

---

# Spaced Repetition Logic

Normal Mode

| User Action | Next Review |
|-------------|------------|
| Correct     | 3 Days     |
| Wrong       | 1 Day      |

Developer Test Mode

| User Action | Next Review |
|-------------|------------|
| Correct     | 3 Minutes  |
| Wrong       | 1 Minute   |

This allows reviewers to test the full review cycle within a few minutes.

---

# Architecture Decisions

## Service Layer

Dictionary API integration is implemented in a dedicated service layer.

Benefits:

- Clean controllers
- Better separation of concerns
- Easier maintenance
- Easier testing

---

## MongoDB Data Model

Each vocabulary word stores:

```js
{
  word,
  definition,
  example,
  nextReviewDate,
  createdAt,
  updatedAt
}
```

The `nextReviewDate` field is used to determine whether a word is due for review.

---

## Error Handling

The backend handles:

- Invalid words
- Dictionary API failures
- MongoDB errors
- Invalid review requests

Appropriate HTTP status codes are returned.

